%I A392500 #20 Mar 03 2026 04:10:21
%S A392500 4,6,8,9,10,14,15,16,20,21,22,25,26,27,28,32,33,34,35,38,39,44,45,46,
%T A392500 49,50,51,52,55,57,58,62,63,64,65,68,69,70,74,75,76,77,81,82,85,86,87,
%U A392500 88,91,92,93,94,95,98,99,104,105,106,110,111,115,116,117,118
%N A392500 Numbers k > 1 whose largest proper divisor cannot be written as a sum of their other nontrivial divisors.
%C A392500 Equivalently, k is a term if and only if it is composite (A002808) but not composable (A392440). We call these numbers 'noncomposable'.
%C A392500 This sequence = A392498 U A392499, thus, noncomposable numbers are either sparse (A392498) or rigid (A392499).
%C A392500 The set of nonnegative integers is the union {0, 1} U A000040 U A392440 U this sequence.
%C A392500 Semiprimes (A001358) are a subsequence.
%C A392500 Strict prime powers (A246547) are a subsequence.
%H A392500 Peter Luschny, <a href="https://github.com/PeterLuschny/Gists/blob/main/ComposableRigidSparse.ipynb">Composable, rigid, and sparse numbers</a>. A Python notebook.
%o A392500 (Python)  # Functions is_sparse and is_rigid are defined in A392498 and A392499.
%o A392500 def A392500_list(upto: int) -> list[int]:
%o A392500     return [n for n in range(2, upto + 1) if bool(is_sparse(n)) or bool(is_rigid(n))]
%o A392500 print(A392500_list(118))
%Y A392500 Cf. A392440 (composable), A392498 (sparse), A392499 (rigid), A002808 (composite), A001358, A246547.
%K A392500 nonn,new
%O A392500 1,1
%A A392500 _Peter Luschny_, Jan 14 2026
